lololololol
First in a progression series

The deck is really good at disableing the enemy's board and providing interuptions.

The best starting hand would be Kshatri-La Papiyas  or Prime Planet Paraisos  and any Kshatri name. My normal combo is as follows

Special Kshatri-La Unicorn , eff of unicorn. Search extender of which you dont have (Field or Papiyas).

Activate Extender to special Kshatri-La Ogre . Ogre eff to search Kshatri-La Prepare .

Overlay for Kshatri-La Shangri-La .

If you have a third name like Kshatri-La Riseheart  or Tearlaments Kshatri-La  then special either they both have on summon eff's to banish your opponents cards. If you drew Psy-Beast normal and use eff then ditch Kshatri-La Fenrir . It becomes a 7 for an extra overlay summon.

Set what evers left and pass. If you draw a Triple Tactics Talent alongside a decent hand it could possibly extend you further by drawing two going first.

In Draw phase activate set cards, special with Kshatri-La Prepare  and put what name you wish. Personally I go for Fenrir or Unicorn BUT, sometimes it can be advantageous to special Ogre, or Tearlaments to mill even more and chain zone blocks in MP1. They have activated effects to banish from extra deck or field. Very useful. Every time you banish you activate the eff of Shangri-La and disable a zone. If done correctly and Arise-Heart is on the field you will have a decent board with decent interuption.

My best board so far is Shangri-La, Arise Heart, Number 89: Diablosis the Mind Hacker , Anti-Spell Fragrance , and Prepare. Maybe Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring  or even Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit  in hand. Turn two gives you second turn kill power with Topologic Zeroboros as well!

Lastly the tech quickplay spell Runick Freezing Curses was added to the deck to not only add a possible negation, but fuel the zone disable and banish plays. All in all its a fun deck! Let me know what you think. :)

Watch my video linked for a better idea.

deck_excerpt: Six searchers for The Great Emperor; still bricks.
deck_description:
Use Foolish Burial Goods to send Ice Barrier to the graveyard, then search for The Great Emperor Penguin, Penguin Squire, Gameciel, the Sea Turtle Kaiju, or Icejade Tremora. Ice Knight , Icejade Tremora, and Royal Penguins Garden all help to summon The Great Emperor Penguin which is the main combo piece. Icejade Tremora, and Gameciel have been left at 1 copy each as they're both searchable.

There are six cards that search for The Great Emperor Penguin (three copies of Royal Penguins Garden, and Foolish Burial Goods each), and six that enable it to be easily summoned (one Icejade Tremora, two Ice Knight, and three Royal Penguins Garden).

Penguin Ninja is at 1 copy since it's a card you can't do much with in your opening hand. You should summon it from the deck alongside Puny Penguin with The Great Emperor Penguin while you have Penguin Squire in your hand. Then flip Puny Penguin face-down with Penguin Ninja to summon Penguin Squire from your hand with its trigger effect, then flip-up Puny Penguin with Penguin Squire's ignition effect to go for round 2 with The Great Emperor Penguin.

Nopenguin is at 2 copies since it's a once-per-turn graveyard effect on a card that is extremely easy to dump into the graveyard. Doesn't really do anything in your opening hand besides act as discard fodder for Royal Penguins Garden.

Puny Penguin is typically dead in your opening hand. It's arguably the best card in the deck, but it's only useful when it is able to recycle The Great Emperor Penguin after having been summoned from the deck by him.

deck_excerpt: Not meta, won't beat anything with a negate, but near-guarantees a win on turn 2/3 otherwise.
deck_description: I've been playing this deck in Master Duel for a while. Made it after someone used the same combo of Shien's Spy, Impcantation Talismandra or Impcantation Candoll, and Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon on me. Basically, I've done everything I could think of to maximize my chances of summoning either Blue-Eyes Chaos Dragon or Chaos MAX. If you have an Impcantation and can special summon it, do so in defense mode. The field spell Impcantation Thanatosis is mainly there to deal with enemy cards, rather than getting your Impcantations out. The easiest way to win with this deck is by getting an Impcantation on the field, using either Shien's Spy or Creature Swap to put it on your opponent's field, then Ritual summon Chaos MAX with one of the Blue-Eyes White Dragons you'll inevitably have laying around with either Advanced Ritual Art or Chaos Form, and have it attack the Impcantation you pawned off. Regular Chaos Dragon exists for when you don't have anything else, or when your opponent builds a board that doesn't immediately nullify your entire playstyle, but still has more than 4000 ATK. Only Ritual Summon it through your regular Blue Eyes. Blue-Eyes Alternative White Dragon and regular Blue-Eyes can also be summoned alongside Chaos Dragon or Chaos MAX by using Impcantations as tributes for an OTK by sheer brute strength, provided your opponent bricks.

deck_name: Shaddoll Branded Grass Skull Servant January 2023 [MD]
deck_description:
Update: After Branded Opening, Aluber of Despia and That Grass Looks Greener were all limited to 2, I decided to finally update the decklist changing it up a bit, most notably adding triple Nemeses Flag for more chances to summon Colossus  

While you could say that the zombie package with Uni-Zombie fits Skull Servants more, the newly added Branded cards are simple better as they offer not only a reliable way to foolish burial Wightbaking thanks to Branded Fusion (Lubellion the Searing Dragon is also just as much of a great discard outlet as Uni-Zombie) but also a great turn 1 play with Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon. We also play a small Shaddoll engine with El Shaddoll Fusion also acting as a foolish burial turn 2 most of the time and triple Nemeses Corridor to summon Thunder Dragon Colossus. Lastly, we of course play That Grass Looks Greener to mill cards like the Wights, the Shaddolls, Despian Tragedy and Fairy Tail - Snow.

deck_excerpt: Very budget competitive deck thanks to the mega tin!
deck_description:
Combo- For a two point five card combo you need acess to tri-brigade fraktall, and lyrilusc turqoise warbler and a card to put back in the deck. You will start by activating fraktall, you will send it from the hand to the grave to send kitt to grave who will send nervall to the grave who will add kerass to the hand. You will then special summon turqoise warbler to the board. Then you can normal summon kerass and use its effect to banish 2 tri-brigade monsters from the graveyard and summon bearbrum from the extra deck. You will then link all 3 of them into an apollousa with 3 negates. When the bearbrum is linked off you will get to search revolt, and put back your blank card. You will set the revolt and pass your endboard is 3 monster negates a non targeting banish a potential 3-4 hand traps, or more dending on what else you oppened, and followup through nervall on the oponets turn.

Budget options- You can swap the crossout designators out for something like skull meister or ghost belle. If you can not afford zeus, then you can play another bearbrum, or omen, or a generic link 2 or 3. If you can not afford accesscode talker then you can play borrelsword, or a genric link monster. even though apolousa is a 20 dollar card it is very important to the deck so you should really play it if you are going to play this deck.

deck_excerpt: The most optimal way to play with the new support
deck_description:
Synchro focused variants of Blackwing have more slots for handtraps/board breakers, plays less bricks, end on boards with multiple forms of disruption that are spread out, and can play through handtraps fairly well, including Nibiru. 

Main Combos:
Simoon + any Blackwing name: (combo created by Kkid)

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=59311-39558849


Suthri: (combo created by Kkid)
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=59311-39964811



Shamal + Vata: (combo created by JTSpeed)
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=458507-41754044

 

Simoon, Suthri, and Shamal + Vata/Black Whirlwind are your main starters. There's more you can do if you open up better, like Suthri + Shamal/Vata/Black Whirlwind/Black Feather Whirlwind, Simoon + Whirlwind, etc. Instead of posting all those, I'll link replays that focus on playing through specific handtraps. On some replays, I skip some setup because almost every Simoon line goes something like -> Simoon, activate Whirlwind -> search Suthri, Normal Summon Suthri, search Vata + Shamal, activate Shamal to activate Feather Whirlwind, Vata special summon + effect to summon Black-Winged Dragon.

Simoon, Ash on Vata: (if they Ash Simoon normal summon, that can end your turn unless you have another name in hand you can normal summon)
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42764806

Simoon, Ash on Wise Strix:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42772481

Simoon, Ghost Belle on Feather Whirlwind:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42772557

Simoon, Ghost Belle on Shamal 2nd effect:
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42774534


Simoon + Gale, Nib on 5th summon (Suthri + Vata/Shamal/Black Whirlwind + Gale also works):
https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42763789

 

Simoon + Gale through Nib on Suthri 2nd NS:

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42763943

 

Simoon + Gale through Nib on Wise Special Summon:

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42764010

 

Simoon + Gale through Nib on FAM summon + Zephyros Bounce:

https://www.duelingbook.com/replay?id=44857-42764156


In actuality, it does not matter where they Nib you so long as you have Gale as an extender. If they decide to Nib you at the very end of your combo, you still end on FAM + Twin Shadow for 2 pops + Chinook. You can also choose to leave Assault Dragon in the ED, if everyone is playing Nib in their side deck or you think your opponent will wait to Nib you at the end,  so then you can summon BWAD afterwards.

Deck Choices and other notes:
- None of the level 4 Blackwing extenders do anything in this synchro build. Your starters already do all the work in getting you to your full combo and opening hands like Suthri + Bora as opposed to just Suthri adds literally nothing to your end board and their level 4 non-tuner stats aren't favorable. Gale, Harmattan, and Oroshi are the only worthwhile extenders. Gale lets you play through Nib via Hawk Joe (also for easier Raikiri access), Harmattan can come up for when you need to synchro Shamal summoned off Wise Strix with Harmattan to make a level 6, and Oroshi let's you summon Hot Red Abyss easily. 
- At least 2 or 3 level 2's are mandatory. 1 is needed to activate Vata's effect to send a level 2 + Zephyros (important), so it won't be a problem if you draw 1 level 2. 
- At least 3 consistency cards are needed (Small World, Prosperity, and Allure are the best ones). You only have 6 1 card starters in the deck, so you need the extra consistency. 
- PK engine adds unnecessary bricks and the endboards aren't that impressive comparing to what you could do in a Synchro focused deck playing minimal bricks. Dark Requiem takes more investment than I:P into Apollousa (using at least 2 monsters you summon off Twin Shadow + Feather Whirlwind on your opponent's turn). Kali Yuga builds can now get away with playing only the 1 Rank-Up Magic Launch as a brick, but the combo is too intricate and fragile to be consistent through handtraps. And you already deserve to be winning if your opponent opened literally nothing to stop your combo. The only advantage Kali has over Synchro is that it doesn't lose to Mystic Mine. 

- The deck has 9 or 10 slots for handtraps/board breakers. Blackwing still struggles going 2nd so board breakers > handtraps.
- You can play Zonda + Kunai > Vayu if you want. They both accomplish the goal of getting a free body on board (preferrably level 5), so you should only play one or the other. Zonda requires you to play another soft brick, while Vayu takes a slot in your Extra deck.
- Optional cards in the extra: Draco Berserker of the Tenyi, Psy-Framelord Omega, Raikiri, Sohaya (if you play the Gamma package)
- Wing Requital is a winmore and terrible because it does NOT get you to your starters.

deck_excerpt: My attempt at a Blue-Eyes + Branded Deck, I just sorta realized how well Despia fits in as well.
deck_description:
So this deck isn't super complicated if you're familiar with how to play a Branded deck, though there are possibly some choices I've made that can be altered to make this deck more consistent.

For starter's, I mostly chose the Blue-Eyes engine cause... well I think it's fun to play and I like seeing Neo-Blue-eyes in a deck. Though weirdly, in my practice with the combos I can get from my starting hands, this deck is actually pretty damn consistent and has a LOT of baits for Ash-Blossom/Called By the Grave. All in all, not a horrid deck but not tier 0 or anything.

A quick rundown of complicated cards;

Despia, Theatre of the Branded is there for a slight protection should any of your big boss fusion monsters be destroyed in any way. Also, an easy way to quickly fusion summon most of your boss monsters should you have a brick of a hand

Dark Pheonix Enforcer is honestly there for the Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon, because the two cards combo ridiculously well

Sage with Eyes of Blue is there in case any of your monster cards are negated or Ash Blossomed, Sage can quickly change them out for a 3000 atk beatstick, which is much better than a dead combo card most of the time.

Again, if you think there are ways that this deck could be significantly improved you're probably right. I am just messin around and trying out something new for me. I usually stay away from meta archetypes (you can look at my other decks for proof of that), but the Branded and Despia archetypes just seem like a good bit of fun, especially since I love fusion monsters more than any other extra deck monsters.

deck_description:
A Labrynth deck that utilizes cards from the "Amazement" theme in order to effectively control the playing field.

Amaze Attraction Viking Vortex can be substituted for Amaze Attraction Thrill Train if you wish.

The Extra Deck is mostly there to be used as fuel for Pot of Extravagance. However it is built under the assumption that you may wish to run Dogmatika Punishment and/or Absolute King Back Jack.

The Side Deck is tailored to go up against common threats at my Local OTS. Different Dimension Ground counters Tearlament, Solemn Judgment and Appointer of the Red Lotus counters strong spell and trap card removal cards such as Harpie's Feather Duster, Evenly Matched helps break an established board when going second, and Summon Limit helps put the brakes on Floowandereeze. 

Because my Side Deck is tailored to combat decks at my Local OTS, you may want to change it up some so that it makes more sense for you.
Cause mayhem with Melffys!

The name saids it all, It's a combination to make a faster and easier way to bring out Chaos Max.
The little odd-eyes and red-eyes are to make more interruptions, you can left them out if you want; hope you find it usefull :D

I think Swordsoul is an easy pick for the Synchro Xyz festival. The idea behind this list was simple, run the Synchro lines from Swordsoul and use reanimation effects to put up Zeus from the rank 4 engine, the Zoodiacs.

The Tenyis still make the cut, even depowered as they are they work too well with the engine to abandon. I'm also running level 4 Tenyis for easy 6 material Zeus lines going second. Baxia and 3 of the Sacred Summit help make this a deck that can solidly break boards while putting up 2-3 interruptions per turn, and still has access to the best Xyz in the format. If you own Dweller or Tornado Dragon you could cut down on Zoodiacs to run more of a toolbox. I actually crafted my Dweller down, and realistically having either a pop or a Zeus is reasonable enough. You try and make synchro plays on the play, and force through Zeus first on the draw (sometimes baiting interruptions on the way). Zeus + Barronne seems to be a good plan in the format.

Deck originaly made by https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC1Wq6f5jFy2jwq9YyISUS1Q Kal_Life I made it on this site so I can easily test it out. I if I do deicided to build this deck I will updatae this with a guide on combos and such.

deck_name: A Comprehensive Guide to Dinomorphia Dragoon (September 2022)
deck_excerpt: Pulled Dragoon, Prosperity and Dimension Shifter? Dinomorphia Dragoon is the perfect anti-meta deck to use them in! Youtube link inside!
deck_description:
I pulled a Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon from my 2022 Megatin Case. Being super excited to finally own one (it's been two years!!!) I frantically looked for a deck that can host this beautiful Duel Monsters Nostalgia bait!

Dragoon is a force of nature on it's own - untargetable, indestructible, 3000ATK, omni-negate, it can increase it's own attack and burn up to twice per turn! Dragoon is a ridiculously powerful card, and getting it out is extremely easy as well with Red-Eyes Fusion being easily accessible. The only downside is that Red-Eyes Fusion prevents any summoning for an entire turn, which seriously prevents Dragoon from being usuable in many decks.

After a lot of research, I've discovered the perfect shell to put the incredibly powerful card in is Dinomorphia. While Dragoon provides an omni-negate Dinomorphia seriously needs, Dinomorphia provides control, a fieldwide one-sided "Skill Drain," and battle protection through Rexturn. Dinomorphia can summon their monsters via their trap cards on the opponent's turn, effectively bypassing Red-Eyes fusion's summon lock!


Paired with Dinomorphia, Dragoon and his Dino DNA squad can even smash through 2022 meta threats like Spright and Tearlaments!

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

ARCHETYPES, ENGINES AND DECKBUILDING

 

  • Forming the deck’s core, The Dinomorphia cards in the Main Deck consist of 15 cards:

3 Therizia, 1 Diplos, 3 Frenzy, 2 Domain, 1 Alert, 1 Brute, 1 Sonic, and 3 Trap Trick. Forming most of the Extra deck, there are 3 Kentregina, 3 Rexturn and 2 Stealthbergia.

  • The Dragoon cards in the maindeck consists of whopping 9 cards:

1 Dark Magician, 1 Red-Eyes Black Dragoon, 1 Red-Eyes Wyvern, 3 Red-Eyes Insight and 3 Red-Eyes Fusion. In the Extra Deck, there are 3 Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. These cards enable arguably one of the most ridiculous cards ever printed by Konami - Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon.

  • Generic Support cards assist the Pure Punk strategy and consist of 7 cards.

3 Pot of Prosperity, 1 Called by the Grave, and 3 Gozen Match.

  • Board Breaker and Staple Handtraps cards consist of 12 cards.

3 Dark Ruler No More, 3 Evenly Matched, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Dimension Shifter. These cards can singlehandidly turn the odds in your favour with their devastating board breaking/turn ending potential.

43 cards are used in this deck to lower the possibility of drawing into bricks/garnets like Dark Magician, Red-Eyes Black Dragon, Red-Eyes Wyvern an Dinomorphia Diplos. Cards can be more easily accessed through Pot of Prosperity. Prosperity is easily used in this deck, since not every Extra Deck monster is needed.

 

 

COMBOS AND GAMEPLAN

 

Dinomorphia Dragoon is fairly easy to play, since it doesn't involve multiple combo routes and complex decision making. Functioning as an anti-meta stun deck, you simply lockdown your opponent with Dragoon/Dinomorphia until they concede or die!

Able to go first or second thanks to the wide variety of devastating board breakers and crippling handtraps, Dinomorphia Dragoon can play either way. Preferably going first is best, since it allows the player to use their Dinomorphia trap cards as soon as possible.

Going first, the gameplan is pretty simple - try to summon Dragoon and set all your trap cards. On the opponent's main phase, summon Kentregina, then summon Rexturn to shut off your opponent's monster effects on their field. This Dinomprhia gameplan is backed by Dragoon's omni-negate and floodgates like Gozen Match/Dimension Shifter, effectively shutting down your opponent's plays.

Going second, boards are broken with a combination of Dragoon + Dark Ruler No More/Evenly Matched. If you are missing a certain card to break your opponent's board, try to dig for it with Pot of Prosperity. After Dragoon is successfully on board, it is a nigh unstoppable juggernaut, capable of destroying two monsters with it's effect and running over another monster in the battle phase. After Dragoon's onslaught, the Dinomorphia cards are ready for action, ready to seal the deal as their summoned on your opponent's next turn with their control/lockdown effects.

If your opponent manages to break through your board and slay Dragoon, Dinomorphia can actually grind out a game by themselves for several turns. Every Dinomorphia monster floats into a monster from the Graveyard, and Therezia/Diplos can grab resources from deck.

Your win condition is Dragoon or Rexturn. If either of those come out, it is often game over for your opponent.

 

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

 

GENERAL TIPS

 

  • Dinomorphia's main gimmick is halving the player's lifepoints to dangerously low levels. Be aware of your attack position/defense position monsters! Note that a simple attack from even a Kuriboh can kill you!
  • Be careful of cards like Sky Striker Hayate that can attack directly, or Spright Pixies which can increase their attack points to hit over your monsters!
  • Fun fact - Gozen Match prevents your opponent from kaiju'ing or Lava Goleming your monsters from your field. Protect your Dragoon and Rexturn with that floodgate!
  • If you already have all the pieces of your gameplan in your hand, use Pot of Prosperity after you thin out your deck so you have the highest chance to get the card you want.
  • Dinomorphia Sonic is this deck's answer to backrow based boardbreakers like Dark Ruler No More, Lightning Storm, Evenly Matched and Triple Tactics Talent.
  • The side deck has many cards that straight-up end your opponent's turn, allowing you to swing back for lethal. Be sure to side in the appropriate cards when you're guaranteed to go first!

 

CONCLUDING COMMENTARY

 

When I held the Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon in my hands when I pulled it from the tins, it was like holding pure power! Proving how powerful it is in online testing, I was amazed how that singular piece of nostalgia bait that seemed like a fan-made monstrosity can tear through meta decks with the greatest of ease!

Dinomorphia Dragoon is a great anti-meta call when facing a format overly reliant on field-based monster effects, targeting removal, destruction effects summon spam, and graveyard reliant strategies. This deck counters all of that through a combination of Dragoon, Rexturn, Dimension Shifter and Gozen Match!

If you pulled or obtained your Dragoonsm Pot of Prosperities and Dimension Shifters just like me, this is the perfect deck to use them in! I definitely am, next time I go to my Locals.

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: Tired of your opponent? Just Zeus them
deck_description:
A blind second version of a fan favorite, which wants to turbo out Zeus and keep pressure by pure card advantage recurring resources each turn with Dante, Cir and Scarm.

As simple as this deck is, it actually requires skill trying to avoid being locked by your own non-BA monsters, and here come in clutch monsters such as Libic, Rhino and even Unicorn at times.

The ratio for Tour Guide may seem a bit odd, but considering all the HandTrap flying around it's best to only run one, that you may search via Scarm's effect. The same thing applies for Rhino: 1 impermanence or 1 veiler and you might pass or even go to the next game.

If you lose the dice roll this time luck may actually be on your side, while going first in G1 you may have a disadvantage. G2 you can just seed in going first cards according to the match-up or keep going second stuff: it's all up to you and how much you want to mess with your opponent's mind.

I had the opportunity to play this deck for around 2 weeks and I faced good players, at local, playing Spright, Tear, Mathmech, but I got the upper hand via the surprise element and good technical plays. My records playing this deck so far are 3-1-0 and 4-0-0.

This build is quite budget and I want to keep it this way 'cause it may encourage people to try this out. 

In the end, if you want to play this deck remember to chain lock, as much as possible, and to use your disruption wisely and in some unexpected ways (Zeus to clear your back-row to make space for your BA plays as an example). Hoping that this may have been useful to you I want to remind you: Chain Link 1 Cir target Dante, Chain Link 2 Dante target Cir :)

This will be a pretty quick breakdown, but I just wanted to get this deck out there as soon as I could! So, the new Kshatri-La cards are pretty powerful. Whenever the opponent activates card effects, you can respond by banishing cards from various zones the opponent controls (field, hand, gy, deck, extra deck). They are splashable as special-summonable Lv 7 mons with good on-field effects, and on their own they form a very strong control core, with each of the monsters banishing cards in reaction to the opponent's monster effects, Shangri-La locking down field zones from being used, and cards like Prepare or Berth summoning back your own banished monsters. Combining this with Runick gives us an even stronger control core, as we can use the excellent Runick removal spells and recursion engine off of the field spell! This build is by no means a perfect list, but I really think that this concept can be innovated and pushed further! The idea is to stun the opponent out of the game, and win either through combat or by decking them out.

 

 Commnents, suggestions, ideas? Let me know what you think!
REDMD.dec

The Dogmatika engine itself is pretty consistent, relying on Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous as the main search, with Dogmatika Adin, the Enlightened as a backup normal summon for this engine. Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted essentially provides a hand trap (if your opponent is playing extra deck, or you manage to keep one on the field) while Dogmatika Ashiyan provides recycle capability, as does sending Titaniklad the Ash Dragon from the extra deck to the GY. Nadir Servant provides another way to start this engine.

The main idea though is to use Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous to gain access to your ritual monsters - White Knight of Dogmatika and White Relic of Dogmatika - and your ritual spells - Dogmatikalamity and Dogmatikamacabre. This might require sending Herald of the Arc Light to get a ritual spell, and if Dogmatika Maximus is in hand, getting an extra deck monster to the GY sets up nicely. Diviner of the Herald is included to add another option for this part of the engine.

Salamangreat Almiraj into Secure Gardna is a quick way to get an extra deck monster in grave, especially with Dogmatika Maximus in hand as this provides further extra deck dump. Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom is a good option to replace a brick in the starting hand, while Lyna the Light Charmer, Lustrous can potentially provide this too as well as disruption.

Preparation of Rites and Pre-Preparation of Rites provide consistency, but I've not figured out the ratio of ritual monsters to use in order to make these two most effective.

Dogmatika Punishment and Shaddoll Schism and Secret Village of the Spellcasters provide nice disruption while Infinite Impermanence is a good game 1 card to have which can be swapped for other hand traps if needed. Effect Veiler is good for a route into link plays as well as hand trap. The Shaddoll extra deck cards are a way to recycle the single Shaddoll Schism.

This is the first deck I've ever built myself, so feedback is more than welcome!

deck_excerpt: This deck combines the Spright engine with the new field-swarming Krawler support!
deck_description:
Hello again! This is a deck in a series of lists where I try to build as many Krawler variants as I can! By doing so I hope to explore unusual builds, interesting synergies, and to give other people inspiration to improve these lists or make lists of their own. In this variant, I'm combining Spright and Krawler, splashing the Frog engine. I'll be going over the archetypes' strengths and weaknesses, the card choices, and the decks combos below!

 

What are the strengths, weaknesses, and synergies of the archetypes in this list? Krawlers have gotten much stronger at flooding the field with the release of Krawler Soma, but their strongest disruptions are Winda and Deus X-Krawler, both of which are vulnerable to removal/negation. Krawler flip-control is a playable strat, using Sol and Luna as well as Mind Meld to answer several of the opponent's monsters, but it requires a lot of main-deck slots to achieve. Krawlers can quite easiliy make Utopic Draco Future, but they rely on out-of-archetype support to extend their plays. Spright need no real introduction. One of the best decks this format, they can easily put up powerful negates, protection for their board, and recurse resources every turn. Spright don't really struggle with any deckbuilding weaknesses, but they benefit from synergistic support. All of the main Krawlers we are using are level 2 (even Soma, after summoning 2 monsters), and so they allow the Sprights to special summon themselves form hand. Krawlers can also build their board before we even commit to the Spright plays, letting us set up a very dense board before passing, or playing through the opponent's interruption if they go first. The combination of these 2 archetypes also lets us play a very toolboxy build, including several answers for threats and combo-paths that we can use to adapt to the opponent's deck as we play.

 

Alright! So, the two main engines we are playing are the Krawler engine and the Spright engine, but we are splashing Frogs, Magicians' Souls, and using Small World for consistency. We are playing 1 Deus X-Krawler (summoned off of the Girsu combo), 3 Soma (the best Krawler and a main playmaker), 2 Glial, 1 Spine, 1 Axon, 3 Mind Meld, 1 Pawns, and 3 Girsu (an honorary Krawler). We want to mill / discard Mind Meld off of Girsu, Magicians', Survivor, or Mothman, but we can also use it to negate an opponent's monster effect, bouncing a monster we control to hand which often doesn't hurt us. Glial is great recursion, and we could play them at 3, but I'm trying to save space. There is an argument for cutting Girsu, but I find them to be an excellent Ash-bait, and if they are not negated we can extend pretty far. If you cut Girsu, also cut Deus (the only consistent way to summon them is off of Mind Meld), and limit Mind Meld to 2. For Spright, we are on 3 Blue (the best), 3 Jet, 1 Carrot, 1 Red, 2 Starter, and 2 Smashers. I find that when playing a mixed-deck with Spright, its best to play Starter and Jet at a 2/3 or 3/2 ratio, depending on whether you prefer a more consistent body on board or a more consistent Blue search. In this list, drawing Blue plus Starter is a bit of a dead draw, so we play 3 Jet instead of 3 Starter. Smashers is at 2 to deal with Mystic Mine, and it does well against Tearlament (banishing instead of destroying), as well as being non-targeting removal.

We are playing Magicians' Souls for more consistency (Illusion of Chaos is the dump and a search) and it lets us turn dead cards in hand into draw power. We will usually be linking Souls off for Spright Elf, or I:P Masquerena. Our Small World bridge is Danger! Mothman, but we can also bridge off of the Souls package, Sprights, or Frogs. Speaking of Frogs, we are playing the smallest package we can; 2 Swap Frog and 1 Ronintoadin. This makes the Toadally Awesome package a lot more fragile, but deck space is very tight in this build, and I'm willing to trade durability for fewer bricks. In the Extra Deck, we are playing the Ghostrick / UDF package, the Winda package, 1 Gigantic and 2 Elf, Lib, Unicorn, I:P, and Avramax. I can absolutely see the argument for Accesscode or Apollousa over some of my choices, but this is what I feel gives the deck the most options and answers.

 

Now we're on to combos! I'll start with a few refreshers for those unfamiliar with the basic Krawler/Spright lines of play, then delve into some optimal opens and how we can extend.

Basic Combos:

(Cards in Hand -> combo)

Girsu: Normal Girsu, sending Mind Meld from deck to GY. Summon a token to both fields, then link off for Lib. Use Lib to set Pawns, then summon Deus X off of the Mind Meld in GY.

Gisru and Soma: Normal Girsu, sending Mind Meld and making tokens. Flip-down Girsu to summon Soma, then use Soma to summon 2 Krawlers (Axon and Spine) face-up. Link Soma and the token for Lib, setting Pawns with Lib, then link the 2 Krawlers for Shaddoll Construct. Use Construct to fusion summon Winda with Construct and the face-down Girsu.

Any Spright and a Lv 2 (or Soma and a normal summon): Normal the Lv 2 mon, then special the Spright. Make Gigantic, detatching to summon Swap Frog. Swap Frog sends Ronintoadin to GY, then link Swap and Gigantic off for Elf. Use Elf to summon back Swap, sending Swap from deck to GY, use Ronin in GY to banish Swap to summon itself, then link off for Toadally Awesome. If you have Soma, normal the monster, then use Soma to get 2 Krawlers on the field, then make Gigantic and follow the above combo from there. Making Toadally Awesome can negate Spell / Traps in addition to monsters, so it can be a better counter against certain decks than using Iblee as a floodgate.

Any Spright and a Lv 2 (or Soma and a normal summon): Normal the Lv 2 mon, then special the Spright. Make Gigantic, detatching to summon Iblee. Link Iblee and Gigantic for Elf, summoning Iblee to the opponent's field. Summon back the Gigantic / Lv 2 / Spright from GY with Elf and extend if possible. Again, we can do the same play with Soma by using the summons off of Soma and Soma itself to make Gigantic, then summon Iblee and make Elf. Iblee floodgates the opponent and certain decks will just fold to her (Tear has a lot of trouble), but other lists can play through it with minimal effort (Floowandereeze); either go for Iblee or Toad, depending on the matchup. Iblee can also help us get to Unicorn / Avramax on following turns using her normal summon effect.

 

Extended Combos:

Girsu, Soma, and Spright Blue / Jet / Starter: Perform the above Girsu and Soma Combo, stopping when you have Lib, face-down Girsu, and 2 Krawlers on field. From here, we can either make Winda and end on a Carrot / Red, potentially with a set Smashers, or we can go into UDF. I won't go over the Winda / Spright Red/Carrot line here, but if you want me to explain it, just ask in the comments. So, for the UDF line, use the 2 Krawlers to make Ghostrick Socuteboss, then overlay for Angel of Mischief. Detatch Socuteboss to search Ghostrick Shot, then use Shot to summon back Socuteboss. Overlay for another Angel, then detatch for Ghostrick Scare. Use the 2 Angels for Utopic Future, then overlay that for Utopic Draco Future. Now you can summon Blue from hand, or use Jet / Starter to summon Blue. From here, follow either of the Spright Basic Combos above, ending on Toad or summoning Iblee to the opponent's field. Again, if you need clarification on these combo lines, just ask and I'll respond!

Girsu and Spright Blue / Jet / Starter: Perform the above Gisru Combo, ending on Lib with a face-down Deus. Summon the Blue, or summon Jet searching Starter to summon Blue. Blue searches Jet / Carrot / Red, depending on what you already have or need, then we can make Gigantic to either summon Swap Frog or Iblee, depending on which line we want to follow, ending with Toadally Awesome or an Iblee on the opponent's field.

I might come back to this section later to add more combo lines, but I'll leave it at this for now.

 

Small World Lines:

(Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  Goal)

 

Krawler / Spright Blue/Jet / Souls / Illusion / Iblee  ->  Mothman  ->  Krawler / Spright / Souls / Illusion / Iblee

Girsu / Illusion / Souls  ->  Spright Blue/Jet  ->  Girsu / Illusion / Souls

Spright / Lv 2 Krawler / Iblee  ->  Swap / Ronin  ->  Spright / Lv 2 Krawler / Iblee

Soma / Iblee / Girsu / Spright Blue/Jet  ->  Illusion  ->  Soma / Iblee / Girsu / Spright Blue/Jet

 

The Side Deck doesn't matter, its just a placeholder for now.

 

Thank you for your time! I hope you enjoyed reading this, and maybe it inspired you to try your own take on an under-used archetype! Any ideas you might have to improve this list, or for a new deck, I would love to hear in the comments below! I appreciate you, and hope you have a good day!
Rainbow crystal

deck_name: Tearlaments pure deck, Tearlaments Kshatri-La,[PHHY] Tearalements Perlegia

deck_description:
Thanks to for coincidentally dueling with me in the Master Duel.

WARNING: This deck can only be played in Master Duel before Sep 30, 2022 or without using banlist.

So, this is an Exodia deck with the help of Zombie monster as the starter. This is not a competitive deck (just pray so that your opponent doesn't negate you). This deck has very long combo, if you still confused reading the combo, just watch the video. Before we go to the combo, let's see the card that should be in the main deck.

Cards that should be in the main deck

1x Right Arm of the Forbidden One 

1x Left Arm of the Forbidden One 

1x Right Leg of the Forbidden One 

1x Left Leg of the Forbidden One 

1x Armageddon Knight 

1x Evil HERO Sinister Necrom 

1x Evil HERO Infernal Gainer 

1x Summoner Monk 

1x Sangan 

1x Treasure Panda 

1x Broken Bamboo Sword 

1x Cursed Bamboo Sword 

1x Horn of the Unicorn 

1x Moon Mirror Shield 

If some of those cards is in your starter hand you can use Magical Mallet to return it to the main deck or if you only have 2 cards that should be in the main deck, you can use Plaguespreader Zombie to return it to the main deck which we'll use in a combo.

Combo

1. There are 5 monster cards to start the combo

- Shiranui Solitaire 

Normal summon it then activate its effect. Special summon Uni-Zombie, activate the 2nd effect and send Plaguespreader Zombie to the GY.

- Uni-Zombie 

Normal summon it then activate the its 2nd effect and send Plaguespreader Zombie to the GY.

- Gozuki 

Normal summon it then activate its effect. Send Plaguespreader Zombie to the GY.

- Samurai Skull 

Normal summon it then activate its effect. Send Plaguespreader Zombie to the GY.

- Plaguespreader Zombie 

Normal summon it then link summon Salamangreat Almiraj.

Note: After this, use Plaguespreader Zombie' s effect to return the cards that should be in the main deck.

2. Activate Plaguespreader Zombie in the GY and special summon it.

3. Link summon Crystron Halqifibrax and activate its effect to special summon another Plaguespreader Zombie.

4. Link summon Crusadia Equimax.

5. Link summon Crusadia Magius.

6. Activate Plaguespreader Zombie in the GY and special summon it to the zone that Crusadia Magius points to.

7. Add Crusadia Arboria to the hand after Crusadia Magius' effect triggered.

8. Link summon Crusadia Spatha.

9. Special summon Crusadia Arboria to the zone that Crusadia Spatha points to.

10. Link summon Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights (don't activate the 1st effect). Then activate its 2nd effect and send 4 Equip Spells with different names to the GY and special summon Armageddon Knight.

11. Activate Armageddon Knight to send Evil HERO Sinister Necrom to the GY.

12. Activate Cursed Bamboo Sword (Chain Link 2) in the GY to add Broken Bamboo Sword to the hand.

13. Activate Evil HERO Sinister Necrom in the GY to special summon Evil HERO Infernal Gainer.

14. Xyz summon Number 60: Dugares the Timeless using Armageddon Knight and Evil HERO Infernal Gainer.

15. Activate the 2nd effect of Number 60: Dugares the Timeless to special summon Armageddon Knight from the GY.

16. Activate Armageddon Knight to send Summoner Monk to the GY.

17. Link summon Aleister the Invoker of Madness using Number 60: Dugares the Timeless and Armageddon Knight.

18. Link summon Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians using Aleister the Invoker of Madness and Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights.

Note: After this, the position of the monsters in the zone is very important. Make sure that you don't mess up or you'll break the combo.

19. Activate Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians to special summon Summoner Monk below (↓) Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians.

20. Activate Summoner Monk then discard Broken Bamboo Sword to special summon Treasure Panda . If you use the Right (→) Extra Monster Zone, special summon it to the Left (←) Corner of the Main Monster Zone, and vice-versa.

21. Activate Treasure Panda to special summon Flamvell Guard to the bottom-right () of Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians.

22. Activate Treasure Panda to special summon 2 pieces of Exodia (Arm/Leg) to the remaining Main Monster Zone.

23. Link summon Striker Dragon using Flamvell Guard to the bottom-right () of Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians.

24. Link summon Firewall Dragon using Selene, Queen of the Master Magicians and Summoner Monk to the left (←) of Striker Dragon.

25. Link summon Union Carrier using 2 pieces of Exodia (Arm/Leg) to the left (←) of Firewall Dragon.

26. Activate Treasure Panda to special summon 1 piece of Exodia (Arm/Leg).

27. Link summon Link Spider using 1 piece of Exodia (Arm/Leg) to the upper (↑) of Firewall Dragon.

28. Activate Firewall Dragon to return 3 piece of Exodia (Arm/Leg) from the GY to the hand.

29. Link summon Cross-Sheep using Firewall Dragon and Link Spider to the Extra Monster Zone.

30. Activate Treasure Panda to special summon 1 piece of Exodia (Arm/Leg) to the below of the Extra Monster Zone.

Note: If the other Extra Monster Zone is empty you can special summon piece (arm/leg) below it. But if the other Extra Monster Zone is occupied by opponent's monster, special summon the piece (arm/leg) below Cross-Sheep.

31. Activate Union Carrier to target the piece of Exodia (Arm/Leg) and equip Sangan to it.

32. Link summon Akashic Magician using Cross-Sheep and Treasure Panda to the Extra Monster Zone upper of the piece of Exodia (Arm/Leg).

33. Activate Sangan in the GY then add Exodia the Forbidden One (head) to the hand.

Tips

- Use Prohibition to ban Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring or Infinite Impermanence.

- Use Called by the Grave to counter Maxx "C", Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring etc.

- Use Crossout Designator to counter the staple.

deck_excerpt: A little combo for your control.
deck_description:
Labrynth is a slow as molasses control deck with the only restriction being that it can only access fiends after activating Welcome Labrynth. But, why not get more aggressive than "summon Ariane, set 5, pass". Enter Tour Guide From the Underworld.

Tour Guide can special Scarm from the deck and go through a Ghostrick line to summon U.F.D. In the process, Alucard will re-add Ghostrick Shot from the GY for free discard fodder. During the end phase, Scarm's trigger can search the level 3 fiend Labrynth Chandraglier who can immediately set a Welcome Labrynth from the deck.

The power of this variant is the additional Tour Guides in the deck which can also be searched via Scarm or stacked by Back Jack. These free bodies can easily convert to powerful fiend links: the Knightmares, Unchained Abomination, and Underworld Goddess of the Closed World. Resetting traps via Lovely Labrynth is just icing on the cake.

Consensus is that Paleozoics are at there best when it is easy to mill a notable number of them to the graveyard. In addition, the Frog engine has always been at home in the deck. You see where I'm going? Let's play all the good cards.

The Sprights and Frogs easily allow a first turn Toadally Awesome. The Tearlaments set up your graveyard, and Merrli being a level 2 aqua is incredible to access Spright combos. But, why play this over pure Spright or pure Tearlament? Trap cards. There is nothing more debilitating to combo decks than setting three after setting up your Toad and possibly even a Dragostapelia.

 

And you will never lose to Mystic Mine ever again.

deck_excerpt: Did you know these were rocks?
deck_description:
Adamancipator is a well known link and synchro spamming deck. However, for a little while, some were very tempted by the existence of the Hex-Sealed Fusions: rock monsters that let you special summon fusions in your synchro deck. During Block Dragon's reign, it was relatively easy to gather the resources to summon Naturia Exterio to lock your opponent from spells and traps.

Now a new fusion exists that is easy to capitalize on: Mirrorjade. Using The Dark Hex-Sealed Fusion and any monster special summoned from the extra deck, you can summon a Mirrorjade. Note that this is a special summon, not a fusion summon, so Mirrorjade's raigeki effect cannot trigger, but the value a banish brings to the Adamancipator board is unparralleled. Afterwards, in your opponent's end phase, you can special an Ecclesia and search Fleurdalis as two free extenders attached to a board breaker and beatstick.

This combo is a perfect use of a Halqifibrax. In addition, Spright Elf can resummon level two tuners summoned by the Halq, bypassing its restriction. Finally, the Elf can summon Halq on your opponents turn to access quick synchros.

There are two major benefits to this deck. It is resistant to Dimension Barrier by utilizeing fusions, links, and synchros. In addition, Mirrorjade is an exceptionally powerful going second card, and can still access interruption on the end phase via Titaniklad and I:P.

If you like Adamancipator and want to get some shocked looks out of people at locals, then this deck is for you!

Some type of shit luke would play

Combo 1: Illusion of Chaos 

Starting hand (example): Illusion of Chaos, Pot of Prosperity, The True Name, Dark Magician, and Timaeus the United Dragon

1. Use Illusion of Chaos 1st effect, add Magician's Rod from your Deck to your hand.

2. Normal Summon Magician's Rod to use its 1st effect, add Dark Magical Circle from your Deck to your hand.

3. Activate Pot of Prosperity effect, banish 6 cards from your Extra Deck face-down, excavate 6 cards from the top of your Deck, add The Revived Sky God to your hand.

4. Activate Dark Magical Circle 1st effect, add either Eternal Soul or Magician's Salvation to your hand from the top of your Deck, place Branded Fusion on top your of Deck.

5. Activate The True Name effect, declare the name "Branded Fusion", exvacate it from the top and add it to your hand, then add Slifer the Sky Dragon from the Deck to your hand.

6. Activate Branded Fusion effect by sending both Fallen of Albaz and Dark Magician from your Deck to the Graveyard as its materials, Special Summon Lubellion the Searing Dragon from your Extra Deck.

7. Use Lubellion the Searing Dragon effect by sending Slifer the Sky Dragon as its cost, shuffle both Fallen of Albaz and Dark Magician into the Deck as its materials, Special Summon Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon from your Extra Deck. 

8. If possible, if you do not already have Eternal Soul in your hand or field: Activate Magician's Salvation, then Set Eternal Soul directly from your Deck.

9. Use Timaeus the United Dragon 1st effect, send either Magician's Rod or Magician's Salvation to the Graveyard, Special Summon Timaeus the United Dragon.

10. Use Timaeus the United Dragon 2nd effect, send itself from the field and Dark Magician in your hand to the Graveyard as its materials, Special Summon either Dark Magician the Dragon Knight or another Red-Eyes Dark Dragoon. (Recommending, Dragon Knight because of Eternal Soul).

11. Set The Revived Sky God face-down, then end your turn.

This is as good as True Draco Eldlich can get. Cycle the Eldlich traps to stay afloat until you acquire true Draco cards. 

*Most hands are pretty consistent with at least two back rows and ways to pull out eldlich monsters 87% of the time. 

*if your opponent is playing a floodgate deck, make sure to side in 1-2 super polys; the extra deck is fodder for Poe, and there are a bunch of general swarm control and monsters of all kinds of types and attributes so that super poly can work with almost any combination. 

*This deck is consistent going first or second, but going second is better in most cases because of the Draco spells, traps, and Aldrich's hand effect. Going first is all right, too. Just make sure to set an apocalypse and wait to summon Draco monsters until your opponent's turn.

*Some basic rules for True Draco in case you've never played it before. 1. If you have true Draco's apocalypse, wait to activate its effect until your opponents turn or when they are about to destroy your true Draco monster or spell/trap. Preferably destroy your spells and traps before your monsters and save yourself with true kings' return.

*If you have a dragon diagram, use it first thing on your turn (if you don't have extravagance), so you can get opponents to negate out of the way or get some fodder for true Draco heritage, starting a combo in general. 

*Eldlich cards are excellent at stalling, and make sure to use conquistador at the correct times; otherwise, you will get destroyed. Save guardian for when your opponent gets out a boss monster or a monster similar to dragoon because that card is pretty much the only way to destroy it other than the apocalypse. If your opponent has a monster unaffected by card effects, you must rely on super poly. 

 

That's about it for the summary. | I have played hundreds of games with this deck, so I know it through and through. I'm sure you'll enjoy playing it too. If you got this far, thanks for reading the summary, I've done hours and hours of research to create the most optimum version of True Draco Edlich because they are two control archetypes I like. Love or hate true Draco/Eldlich, just try it out. You are bound to have some fun. I selected this deck as meta because it is top-of-the-line anti-meta and can compete with decks such as sword soul and marincess. Thanks for reading,g and enjoy the gameplay (I am working on other-metal decks, stay tuned for more). HAPPY DUELING!

deck_excerpt: Machines from different times, working together to overpower the strongest of foes
deck_description:
Hi everyone! This is my first submission for a deck on this website. I like to play some more competitive and rogue decks - like Sharks XYZ and PK P.U.N.K, but always have a spot to play "fun/casual" decks as well because, why not? This is one of these decks.

I first got inspired to build this deck after watching DarkArmedDuelist's profile from a year ago. After facing so many control decks, I was wondering what kind of deck would be fun to play that is not in the current meta, and could handle certain decks and playstyles, like Swordsoul. Meklords seemed like an interesting anti-synchro deck, and also had the means to out back-row heavy decks, like Mystic Mine Burn, or even Eldlich. But I knew it wasn't strong enough on it's own. That's when I remembered King Regulus was a card, and could equip machines in the graveyard... and that's how we got to here.

The main idea of the deck revolves around two cards: Meklord Army Recruiter Obbligato, and Meklord Nucleus Infinity Core. These cards enable you to either pop the core to bring out one of your emperors (Weisel for spell negates, or Granel to do some damage), or obbligato to bring out two Meklord army monters - which enable either xyz plays, or link plays. By sending enough of these monthers to the graveyard, you can also build up a pool of monsters with different names, which is what you need to bring out Astro Dragon - which can equip a monster from your opponent's extra deck to boost it's attack power (and potentially attack multiple times as well). 

This deck also plays a lot of going second staples - like DRNM and Feather Duster - to help clear your opponent's board and limit their interuptions/floodgates that could limit your play options. And by adding Therion cards, as well as Kaiju's and Lava Golem in the side deck, it also helps you tribute over monsters that would cause you trouble. And with Astro Dragon Triskelion, you can usually equip an ED monster large enough to get over your own Kaiju.

This deck is by no means perfect, but I hope you enjoy the idea!

deck_excerpt: The Shogunate of New Clear World
deck_description:
Kshatri-las are a Lv7 varied attribute Psychic-type monsters focusing on XYZ summoning and Banishing cards Face-down.

 

The Red Shogunate:

The 3 Original Kshat’s have the effect of Special Summoning themselves if you control no monsters and their Banish effects trigger if your opponent activated a monster effect, meaning that if your opponent tries to stop your plays with monster handtraps they will get screwed over.

 

  • Kshatri-La Unicorn: Spell searcher, and it banishes 1 card from your Op’s Extra Deck

 

  • Kshatri-La Fenrir: Monster searcher, and it banishes 1 card from your Op’s Field

 

  • Kshatri-La Ogre: Trap Searcher, and it excavates the top 5 cards from your Op’s Deck and banishes 1 card among them

 

The newer Support removed that Special Summon and Banish effect on response to monster effects for more consistency and searching.

 

  • Tearlaments Kshatri-La: Can be SS by banishing a Kshatri-la card from your Hand or GY, once summoned it mills 3 cards from either player to the GY, if it is banished it sends 2 cards from your deck to the GY. (This card has great synergy with their new Xyz allowing you to generate resources)

 

  • Kshatri-La Riseheart: The only non lv7 monster in the archetype, it SS itself if you control a Kshatri-la Monster locking you into Xyzs, if it's summoned it can banish a Kshatri-la Monster from your deck and make itself a Lv7. (Basically works as a second copy of Fenrir if you have Kshatri-la Berth)

 

Misc:

 

 

  • Dimension Shifter: DS is here because you benefit from your cards being banished while it also interrupts most meta decks like Tearalaments and Sprights when you are going second.

 

  • Dinowrestler Pankratops: Big boy Pank just happens to be a Lv7 that SS itself if your Opponent controls more Monsters than you, its quick-effect tribute to destroy allows you to interrupt combos or floodgates that affect cards on the field

 

  • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring: because it hits most decks

 

Spells:

 
 

 

  • Prime Planet Paraisos: Like Reichnophobia and Pelereino it adds an archetypal Monster from your Deck to your Hand, it also provides interruptions in pair with Kshatri-la Shangri-la which happens very often due to the deck doing a lot of plays during the opponent’s turn.

 

  • Kshatri-La Berth: Allows you to Normal summon a Lv7 from your hand without tributes, it also allows you to revive banished or dead Kshatri-las. It also has an additional effect to banish 3 cards from your opponent’s GY if they activate or use the effect of a Spell card, fueling your Xyzs.

 

  • Kshatri-La Papiyas: Is a free SS from deck and recovery once banished

 

Misc:

 

  • Terraforming: Consistency is always good

 

  • Reinforcement of the Army: Searches Riseheart

 

  • Sacred Sword of Seven Stars: Free draws and provides targets for Berth

 

  • Called by the Grave: Hits most pesky handtraps

 

Traps:

 

  • Kshatri-La Prepare: Works like Berth but during your opponent’s turn but instead of summoning from the GY it summons from Hand. And if your opponent uses a trap while this card is face-up on the field it allows you to just look at their hand and banish 1 card in it.

 

  • Kshatri-La Big Bang: It works similarly to Evenly Matched but it only works on monsters and requires you to have an Kshatri-la Xyz, If banished it allows you to take a Kshatri-la attached to an Xyz and special summon it.

 

  • Infinite Impermanence: It's the best handtrap in the Format so why not

 

The Extra Deck:

 

  • Kshatri-La Shangri-La: This fire Xyz allows you to summon a Kshatrila monster from your deck during the standby phase, it has protection in form of detaching materials and a non once per turn effect that blocks 1 monster and spell/trap zones whenever anything gets banished face-down allowing you to just lockdown your opponent.

 

  • Kshatri-La Ariseheart: Their new Xyz is just Macro cosmos on legs, whenever anything is banished, once per chain, it can attach 1 card from the banished zone to it, and it can detach 3 to opt banish card face-down, this effect pairs well with Divine arsenal so bad, it makes big unga bunga man and gives it 10 mats to ruin your opponent’s life.

 

  • Number 89: Diablosis the Mind Hacker: While not a Kshatri-la monster (even though he looks like one) peeps into your opponent’s ED and banishes 1 card from it face-down. Whenever it destroys anything by battle it can banish 1 card from your Opponent’s GY. And the most busted effect, it anything your opponent controls is banished face-down it can banish cards from your Op’s deck equal to their face-down banished cards, which in most cases results in 10 cards being banished, and in the consecutive turn 20.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

*Columns exist* Yes... It's MEKKIN TIME!!!!!

This classic 4 year old blind second deck still can smash it's way through current meta, especially in Masterduel!

No in-depth explanation for this decklist, Mekk-Knights are fairly straight forward and already figured out. :)

Clear your opponent's board to create a simplified gamestate with this deck's many boardbreakers, then methodically force a grind game with Mekk-Knight's swarm, beatdown and resource gathering ability. This is mainly done with the 10 searchers this deck has access to, that being Mekk-Knight Purple Nightfall, Blue-Sky, Orcust Girsu, and World Legacy's Memory.

Hard-to-out extra deck bosses are usually the win condition in this deck, like a I:P Masquereena boosted Avramax, an untargetable/undestroyable Mekk-Knight Spectrum Supreme or the column-dependent battle phase champion Mekk-Knight Morning Star.


In a simplified gamestate vacuum, Mekk-Knight Avramax is nigh-unkillable and often is a "checkmate" on your opponent. Zeus can also be used comfortably in this deck, enabled by easy access to Mekk-Knight Orcust Girsu -> Galatea -> Dingirsu.

GLHF Duelists!

deck_excerpt: What do you mean he's got 30,000 Attack?!
deck_description:
This is a Going second beatdown deck. As the name implies, the main strategy for this deck is to banish as many cards as possible, then Normal summon Gren Maju Da Eiza  and attack for game. You achieve this with cards like Pot of Desires/Extravagance, Eater of Millions, and Fairy Tail- Snow.

There are also several monsters that benefit from having a ton of banished cards, such as Eater of Millions, Necroface, and Helios- The primordial sun.

If you need some extra damage, there is also a Banquet/D.D. Dynamite engine in the deck, as well as Golden Castle of Stromberg.

If your opponent manages to stop the Gren Maju, don't worry; the deck has a backup plan. You have a wide variety of level 8's at your disposal; Hexe Trude, Gizmek Orochi, and Gadarla are all level 8's. If necessary, you can summon Number 97: Draglubion to Special summon Numeron Dragon, which will have a minimum of 9,000 attack. After that, you can summon Zeus for a free board wipe.

If you are going first, your best bet is to use Golden Castle of Stromberg and Macro Cosmos, two floodgates that work perfectly in this deck.

Basically, It's 3 OTK decks in one.

deck_description: This is a deck made using the most recent cards that Atem would use without any meta additions. No Dragoon. This deck is mainly based of the Dark Side of Dimensions deck Atem used during his simulated duel against Kaiba. The Face Card Knights didn't fit with the Egyption esthetic of the deck so I sided it alongside Slifer. You can add them if you wish. The god cards, in general, are too bricky to be added. No Timaeus because he no longer owned it after the Waking The Dragons arc. Buster Blader culd be added but would be bricky and his DSOD deck mainly focuses on his older Duelist Kingdom cards like BLS, C. Guardian, and Gaia. My reasoning for adding Super Soldier is due to the mention of it in Chaos Form and the official promotional video by Konami features Atem from DSOD summoning the card (look up Battles of Chaos trailer on YouTube). Adding Gaia was because it is a more recent support of him and Super Soldier floats into a Gaia monster when destroyed. Exodia was added because it fits with the theme and was featured in the 2019 World Championship live duel of Yugi vs Kaiba along with Apprentice Illusion Magician, Magician of Chaos, Magician of Black Chaos Max, Palladium Oracle Mana, and Quintet Magician. I also added the support cards from the 2016 World Championship live duel and the Dark Illusion set except the XYZ because this deck is kept in canon with the DM era. If you have any questions, feel free to comment.

deck_excerpt: A storm's brewing in the forest!
deck_description:
This is a control deck using two synergized archetypes, Melffy and Spright; I've played it locally for the past month with solid results, including a match win against Mystic Mine. It started as a $30 pure Melffy deck with Spright Gamma Burst x2 for surprise, and after some extra homework I managed to incorporate just enough Spright cards to improve the Melffy strategy without losing their soul...

And then I added Divine Arsenal AA-Zeus - Sky Thunder as last-gasp control card.

 

I firmly believe that this deck could make it up the ladder in the meta. If you have any suggestions, I'd love to hear them in the comments!

 

Melffys


The Melffy strategy is to play during your opponents turn, disrupting their moves and sniping choke points with targeted spot removal. The main deck Earth monsters swarm the field during your turn with their End Phase effect, which lets you special summon them to the field if they're in your hand at the end of your turn. Melffy Pinny , the lone Water and Tuner monster, is best kept out of your hand during your turn because it lacks this effect. During your opponent's turn, they begin popping back to your hand to launch their combos:

 

  • Melffy Puppy to hand, search deck and summon Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest, activate effect on summon to destroy any one (1) card on the field.
  • Melffy Catty to hand, search deck and add Melffy Pinny to the hand, then summon it using effect triggered by Catty and immediately turbo out a synchro monster such as:
    • Merry Melffys - which on summon returns a monster to your opponent's hand.
    • Desert Locusts - which on summon discards a card from your opponent's hand, then lets you turbo out a bigger Synchro like
      • Adamancipator Risen - Dragite - which is now a backrow negate.
      • Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend - which can nuke your opponent's board and burn them for 500 a piece during your turn.
    • Virtual World Beast - Jiujiu - which becomes immune to destruction and has a nifty banish mechanic for good measure.
  • Melffy Wally to hand, search deck and summon Melffy Puppy and Melffy Catty. An excellent opening play.

 

Melffy Catty is an exceptional starter card to land on, but don't count out Puppy. You need Puppies to pull Kalantosa out of the deck. Kalantosa may be a brick on the field after summon, but it feeds into the Melffy Xyz cards nicely by providing material for summons and second-act combo.

 

  • Joyous Melffys can send any beast Xyz monster back to the Extra Deck and summon monsters equal to the target's material from the GY during your opponent's turn.
    • If you build Joyous Melffys, Melffy of the Forest, or even Melffy Mommy with Kalantosa, Mystical Beast of the Forest you get to pop at least one - possibly all three - back onto the board and activate that card destruction effect for each copy you bring out of the GY.
      • You can also use this effect to reset your board quickly for more Main Deck disruption!
    • Joyous Melffy can also detach a material to enable all your Mellfys to attack directly that turn. If your first Joyous Melffy went to the GY instead of returning to the Extra Deck, pulling it out with your second copy's effect above could hit your opponent with 4000 ATK (if it can survive until your turn, when this effect activates).

But be warned: timing is everything. Melffy of the Forest is your early-game/first-turn target and Joyous Melffys is your late-game target. This is because Melffy of the Forest allows you to search your deck for sany Melffy Card and add it to your hand. This gives you access to your backrow pieces once per turn, and you'll want them to survive with Level 2 Beasts. Key targets include:

 

  • Melffy Staring Contest - a two-way continuous spell which relieves your hand of beast bricks like Kalantosa and Alpha, the Master of Beasts  in exchange for a Melffy monster AND nerfs your opponent's monsters of 400 ATK for every Melffy monster in your hand during their Battle Phase.
  • Melffy Hide-and-Seek - a two way continuous spell which protects all beast monsters from card effect destruction once AND returns 3 different beasts in your GY to draw one card. Useful when your hand runs out.
    • Also useful for protecting your board when Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend activates its effect, since you don't generate burn damage from your own monsters being destroyed
  • Melffy Tag  - a quick spell that can bring a Melffy onto the field from the GY when your opponent least expects it. Great during their battlephase for bringing out a forgotten-about Melffy Wally from last turn and using its on-battle-target effect.

Melffy Notes

Obedience Schooled is a powerful starter and stall-buster. If you happen to have Melffy Hide-and-Seek on the field too, the monsters it summons won't be destroyed at the end of your turn by its effect. Great for piece of mind if you end up with a straggler after using the first two monsters to summon.

Spiritual Forest protects your Melffy's like Melffy Hide-and-Seek, but this time from battle destruction and it only works on the first monster that turn. Not great, not terrible, definitely useful though since your Melffy's arent helpful in the GY (except for Melffy Pinny).

Alpha, the Master of Beasts is a good card for clearing boards during your turn AND for summoning out in a pinch for extra firepower, since Melffy ATK doesn't add up to much without a few Extra Deck monsters. It's effect will also trigger Melffy Pinny's special summon effect, providing a one-turn option for using Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend. during your turn. 

Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder  is here as a panic button. With Xyz Monsters pulling serious weight in the extra deck, you're going to end up with opportunities to summon it after battle.

Melffy Mommy is fun to say! It isn't as fun to play. It accumulates material steadily, but the effects don't kick in until its 3-under, and you really want it at 5-under in order to crash it into boss monsters for burn damage. The real value proposition here is using it as a summon target for Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder after Joyous Melffys attacks. You could also use it as a target for Joyous Melffys' Quick Effect if you need to replenish your field with disruption cards.

Melffy Playhouse is great late game when you need to clear your opponent's board and you have Melffy Xyz monsters with material on hand. Otherwise, it clogs the field. Using it early-game isn't super useful since everything returns to the hand unless the situation you're in lets you take lots of advantage of a card being gone (ex. Mystic Mine removal during your turn).

Melffy Pony is at one because it is useful for returning cards from the GY to the hand, but only occasionally. It's also a good fodder target for Melffy Hide-and-Seek and Virtual World Beast - Jiujiu.

Melffy Fenny is not included because I only ever used it to out Kalantosa if it ended up in my hand. Melffy Staring Contest does that better by putting it in the deck and exchanging it for Melffy Puppy.

Melffy Rabby is not present on its own, but is with us in spirit. <3

I just wrote 1,111 words about Melffy combos.

Spright

The goal of the Spright engine here is to make Melffys less vulnerable to your opponent. They accomplish this in three ways:

 

Negation support:

Melffy's just don't do negation all that well. Melffy of the Forest has an effect that allows you to negate effect and attack if a card is returned to your hand, but that's not very robust. That's why these common Sprights are here:

  • Spright Carrot negates back row counters once per turn, including juicy plays like Infinite Impermanence and all sorts of backrow destruction. If you have a Link/Rank 2 monster handy for cost, it can destroy the card too.
  • Spright Red negates monster effects once per turn. This is super handy against Invoked Branded Dogmatika. If you have a Link/Rank 2 monster handy for cost, it can destroy the card too.

They both special summon themselves if you have a level 2/link 2 monster on the field, and since this deck includes 22 such cards, getting them out isn't a challenge. It's finding them in the first place. That's why there is one copy each of Spright Starter and Spright Jet as well.

  • Spright Starter searches the deck for a Spright monster of our choice in exchange for LP equal to its ATK. It's second effect locks us out of our Synchros, Alpha, and Zeus for a turn, but that's okay 90% of the time. As a quick spell, this can also be used as a surprise during your opponent's turn.
  • Spright Jet - on special summon, search the deck for one Spright Spell/Trap. If you manage to draw this early, you can use it to pull Spright Starter out. If you pull it late, you can use it for Spright Gamma Burst instead. That leads to our next strategy:

Note: I included two trap cards, Magic Drain and Black Horn of Heaven, and Synchro monster Herald of the Arc Light  for extra negation options.

Beatdown support:

Melffy's aren't very strong. Their biggest monsters only pull out 2000 ATK. After all your disruptions and negations, you'll still need to make the most of your turn when your opponent's board is defenseless. Sprights are great for this because they pack more power then Melffys and they swarm pretty quickly. With the help of the Extra Deck Sprights and a super-sticky power-up spell, we can make the most of our Battle Phase.

  • Spright Elf - a Link 2 monster with a quick effect that summons one Level 2 monster from the GY during the Main Phase. All your Melffy's can be targeted, save for Merry Melffys , as well as your Sprights. Super helpful for extending your play options and building up your board.
  • Gigantic Spright - a Rank 2 monster that doubles its ATK to 3200 points if there's an Extra Deck monster attached as material. It can also special summon any Level 2 monster from your deck for 1 material. When you do this, it activates a 1-turn special summon floodgate that only allows Level/Rank/Link 2 through.
    • Spright Elf into Gigantic Spright was built in by design. Use it wisely for a 1-turn beatstick.
  • Spright Gamma Burst - a quick spell that increases the ATK and DEF of all Level/Rank/Link 2 monsters on the field by 1400 points until the end of the turn. While in the GY during your turn, it can be banished to increase the ATK of one Level/Rank/Link 2 monster of your choice by 1400 points again until the end of your opponent's turn.
    • Build up your field using Spright Elf , Gigantic Spright , Melffy Wally , or even Melffy Mommy + Joyous Melffys and then throw down Spright Gamma Burst for overwhelming Battle Phase advantage. Using this with Joyous Melffys detach effect can win the duel. 
    • If you only have your weaker Main Deck Melffy's, activating this during your opponent's Battle Phase could save them from destruction by battle.

Lockdown support:

During less-than perfect boards, Sprights can save your board from complete annihilation and give you the time to set up for your combos next turn.

  • Spright Elf protects the monsters it points to from card effects. Melffy's make for excellent protection targets, as do our Main Deck Sprights.
  • Gigantic Spright can lock your opponent out of handtraps like PSY-Framegear Gamma, Nibiru, the Primal Being, and Artifact Scythe when it uses its detach effect.
    • Link 2 Beat-Warrior Bujinki Ahashima provides an extra option for spot removal as it allows for an immediate Xyz Summon from the hand and GY upon being link summoned; if you can use that Xyz monster's detach effect AND remember to place it in zone that Bujinki points to, it can destroy a backrow card.
  • Spright Carrot  and Spright Red can save your board with their negation effects when timed right.

deck_description: Just like my previous Blue-Eyes deck, this list focuses on summoning Crystron Halqifibrax by using one of our Blue-Eyes tuners and an extender, this time our extender is not a Chaos Dragon like Collapserpent or Wyverburster but Blue-Eyes' own Dictator of D. which special summons itself and has a neat extra effect to summon a Blue-Eyes monster which helps with synchro and XYZ summons; Dictator also allows us to make the new card Dharc the Dark Charmer, Gloomy. In addition to Dictator, Blue-Eyes Jet Dragon is another new card for the deck, which can be searched by The Melody of Awakening Dragon or be summoned off of a second The White Stone of Ancients during our turn 1 combo. As for said turn 1 combo, here it is: summon Crystron Halqifibrax to bring out The White Stone of Ancients, which is then linked off or used as synchro material in order to activate it's graveyard effect during the end phase, allowing us to summon Blue-Eyes Abyss Dragon and search Chaos Form and any of our turn 3 dragons like Blue-Eyes Chaos MAX Dragon, Chaos Dragon Levianeer or Nebula Dragon if you already used Levianeer in your first turn. Then, during the opponent's turn, you use Halqifibrax's effects to go into Formula Synchron drawing a card and then going into Baronne de Fleur using the level 2 Formula Synchron and the level 8 dragon you summoned off of the White Stone of Ancients last turn, all still within the opponent's turn.

deck_description:
Standard Timelord deck with alternatives that allow you to swap out certain cards for others to make it more versitatile for TCG & OCG

Note: since Imperial Order is forbidden, swap it for Prohibition to maintain similar effect.

This is a Going Second deck which uses the Deskbot archetype.

 

I've only done a bit of testing with this specific deck and it is certainly not complete, as I'd surely be able to further add more into it, but I simply wanted to share my version of this one archetype I love.

 

Some cards can be cut from the Extra Deck, like the 2nd copy of Herald of the Arc Light, 2nd and 3rd copy of Deskbot Jet and cards such as Apollousa.

 

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 

Your main combo starters for this deck are Urgent Schedule (Deskbot 001 + Any other Deskbot, except for 009), Deskbot 003 or any Deskbot 002 or 004 and a Machine Duplication, though the latter is not recommended.

 

The combos in this deck are very simple, as most lines go through a Deskbot 001 and any other monster into Crystron Halq, though what they excell at are branching out into other things you may need to OTK.

What you mainly want to do is:

- Start off with Deskbot 003 or Urgent Schedule and with its effect summon a Deskbot 001. 

- Next, summon Crystron Halqifibrax using both monsters as material, and with its effect summon yet another Deskbot 001. 

- Following that, use both cards as material for the link summon of Auroradon, summon all 3 tokens and use Deskbot 001's effect to summon both to the field. 

- After this, you can go into either Deskbot Jet in order to cycle through Deskbot monsters and further enhance your field or go into Baronne de Fleur to prevent opponent's interruptions.

 

Good luck, duelist.

deck_name: Slifer of Branded Magic (3 Card Combo?)
deck_description:
The 3 card combo is so easily setup.

You can search DM Circle (with Rod); use it to pick up DM and/or DM related Spell/Trap card (usually add Navigation, if not, then Eternal), then if you do that, you can stack Branded Fusion, Trap Trick, Revived Sky God, or Pot of Prosperity (if either of them is not already in your hand). Use True Name to add Revived Sky God (if not, use it for Prosperity for an additional searcher for it), then if you do, summon Slifer the Sky Dragon with True Names effect from the deck, then if you do that, activate Branded Fusion to send both DM and Albaz from the deck to the GY to make Lubellion, then, use Lubellions effect to make either Dragoon or DMtDK (if use use the Eternal build, its high recommended either way). Then, set both Eternal/Navigation and Revived Sky God face-down on your field until the opponents turn.
