broke boy deck

Cyberdarks focus on equipping Dragon and Machines from the GYs to themselves to boost their stats and effects. Typically a going first deck, the aim is to summon "Cyberdark End Dragon", a 5000 ATK monster that is immune to activated effects and can attack multiple times, on the first turn.

Harpie's are my favourite Archetype to play and thanks to some broken support they are a great option to win games left and right especially in Master Duel. Let me explain a bit more in Detail:

 

The big Potential

Your go to Combo is summon Cyber Slash Harpie Lady and set a Feather Storm and sometimes a Harpie Conductor on top of it. Your opponent summons any monster and you activate Feather Storm, chain Cyber Slash to bounce his Monster and win next turn. Any kind of backrow will be no problem thanks to their easy access to the Field Spell. It's also heavily effective against stronger strategies like the Adventure Engine for example.

If you set a Hysteric Sign and destroy it yourself with your field spell you can add any 3 Harpie cards from the deck to your hand during the End phase. Alternatively discard it with Hysteric Party since it triggers from hand too. 

Setting Feather Storm is highly effective since an opponents Lightning Storm/Feather Duster were you chain Feather Storm results in the Monster Effect negate plus a Feather Duster search/recycling on top of it which can't be ashed.

The Harpie's pet Phantasmal Dragon can give a hard time to your opponent when combined with Conductor. Crush (Once per Turn Conductor), targeting and attack protection for all Harpie Monsters isn't easy to overcome for some decks plus he attacks directly and sets the opponent on a 2 - 3 turn clock to find a out to him. And he can be used to create a 4 material Zeus as a added bonus. 

On top of that their new Harpie's Pet Dragon is way less bricky and sets up Harpie Harpist searches for the End phase. He can also create a permanent attack wall when combined with the Baby Pet Dragon.

 

The Ups and Downs

High searchability, recycling, OTK, defensive, removal and stun plus many options make this deck such a hard time to beat for many meta oriented decks.

But there are a few downsides obviously... If your initial normal summon gets removed from field you have literally no follow up outside of setting Hysteric Party and hoping for the best. There are ways to protect your important first summon but a card as simple as Trap Hole is the demise of the Deck. Good that no one plays that card:)

 

Final Words

I find it easy again and again to reach Diamond 1 with this strategy. I do have a lot of practice with it and can't explain every combo in detail here but there's much to look forward too, should you decide to try out this Deck^^

Overall Rating:

deck_excerpt: Extend the Ninja combo lines with Krawler Soma to end on an additional Winda or UDF!
deck_description:
Hello! This is another deck in a series I'm making where I try to come up with as many different Krawler builds as I possibly can, mixing archetypes and splashing engines to make unique builds! This build is primarily a Ninja build, using the new support, with the Krawler Soma engine enabling UDF and Winda. This list leans very heavily on Zefer's Ninja build (please go check out their build, the deck description gives you a great breakdown of the archetype and what it can accomplish!). Again, I really encourage you to click the link above and check out their deck list first; my list is fully inspired by their deck build and what it is able to accomplish. Usually, I try to take mix-up the deck's I take inspiration from, but I tested and could not find better ratios or include's than in that build, and the changes I made are fairly minor. As usual, I will break-down the archetypes in this list, go through a few of the card choices, and give a description of a few of the deck's combos!


Please refer to Zefer's build for the Ninja breakdown; it is very complete and I believe it gives a great profile of what Ninjas can now accomplish with the new support.  I'll go over the new cards in more depth to give some background, which I hope will mesh well with Zefer's explaination. Ninja Grandmaster Hanzo can search Ninjas and Ninjitsu Arts to hand, and this is NOT a once-per-turn ability. As for the new Ninjas; Mitsu is an extender that can represent a negate on board, Baku recurses resources when searched and summons itself, Kagero can bounce your cards to protect their effects from negation and can summon a body face-down, and Green Ninja can flip monsters face-down and summon themselves form hand. The new trap, Ninjitsu Art of Fallen Leaves' Dance, can tribute your Ninjas, or ANY face-down monster (I will use this in another Ninja build I upload) to summon a Ninja from deck (Hanzo / Black Dragon / Mitsu). The Novel Ninjitsu Art Book sets a card from the GY and another from the deck, but it requires the opponent to control a card (very useful for recycling). Ninjitsu Art Equipment Kanamugura lets you treat any monster as a Ninja, can pop a card on board, and when destroyed it returns a banished Ninja to the field or hand. Finally, War Ninja Meisen is a contact-Fusion boss monster for Ninjas. They cannot be targetted for attacks while you control a face-down monster, they let your Ninjas attack directly, and they let you special summon a Ninja when the opponent activates a card or effect! Our Krawlers are fairly minimal in this deck, running 3 Soma, 1 Glial, 1 Axon, and 1 Spine. We are using the Krawlers either at the end of our Ninja combo, or when our combo gets stopped by hand-traps and other negation, to extend our plays. With the new support for Ninjas, there is potential for a pseudo-flip-deck of sorts that I will be exploring in another deck breakdown, but for now the synergies we will be exploring are the combo-extension of both archetypes and the toolbox elements of both archetypes.


So, as you can see, most of this list is the same as Zefer's build. From their deck breakdown you will find that our main combo starter is getting 2 Warrior monsters on the field, which explains the ratios of Hanzo, Fire Flint Lady, and Tobari. The Ninja ratios are almost all the same with the exeption of Kagero which I run at 1 (I didn't feel that I was getting value out of the second copy). The main departures from the list are Pot of Avarice, the Armor Ninjitsu Art of Alchemy / Ninjitsu Art Notebook package, the Krawler package, and the UDF / Winda packages in the extra deck. In the main deck, we miss out on further defensive options like Mist Valley Apex Avian and Ninjitsu Art of Transformation, or Triple Tactics Talents, but I felt I did not have room for these cards, and in testing I favored the other cards I subbed in (this is a personal take and by no means an absolute, feel free to play with the card choices and ratios on your own to figure out what works best for you). The Krawler package consists of the afore-mentioned monsters, as well as 2 copies of Small World, which can either search a Ninja starter or Soma. I found that this deck often runs through its resources very quickly and has trouble turn 2 if the opponent breaks our board, so the Pot of Avarice choice is here to address that issue. Would this problem be better solved by including negates for the opponent's board breakers? Probably, but I'm on a Pot of Avarice kick right now; I just like its inclusion. The Ninjitsu Art Notebook package works by discarding a Ninja to search any Ninjitsu art; this can be used to get a trap on the field for plays during the opponent's turn, or can be used to set then activate Armor Ninjitsu Art of Alchemy for a draw 2. We sacrifice stopping power and consistency in the Extra Deck (Accesscode and 2nd copies of our Ninjas) for the UDF and Winda packages, both of which can be made after a full Ninja combo as an additional layer of disruption.


For combos, I will pick up where Zefer's leaves off. After getting 2 Warriors on field, we can go through Isolde, Saryuja, Getsuga, Zealantis, and Cross-Sheep, ending on a board with Apollousa, Meisen, Hanzo, and perhaps one other Ninja. From here, we can special summon Soma by flipping Hanzo face-down and summon 2 Krawlers from deck. If you want to make Utopic Draco Future, summon 1 Krawler face-up, the other face-down, and if you want to make Winda, summon both face-up. Either link the face-up Krawers into Construct then fuse Winda with the face-down Hanzo, or use the face-up Soma and Krawler to go through the Ghostrick line, ending on Utopic Draco Future and a set Ghostrick Scare. I can provide a more in-depth explaination of the lines this deck can make, but I feel that Zefer does a great job at explaining the main points of the combo, and the inclusion of the Krawler engine is mostly here to supplement that. If we get negated on our Hanzo or Upstart Golden Ninja, we can still make Winda/UDF if we have a Soma in hand, and that is the other upside of this partnership, the ability to play through disruption.


Here are the Small World Bridges:

Starter  ->  Bridge  ->  Goal

Soma / Green Ninja  ->  Mitsu  ->  Soma / Green Ninja

Lv2 Krawler / Mitsu / Hanzo / Upstart Golden / Kagero / Getsuga / Gearfried  ->  Green Ninja  ->  Lv2 Krawler / Mitsu / Hanzo / Upstart Golden / Kagero / Getsuga / Gearfried

Fire Flint / Krawler  ->  Tobari  ->  Fire Flint / Krawler

Kagero / Green Ninja / Upstart Golden / Gearfried / Fire Flint / Soma  ->  Getsuga  ->  Kagero / Green Ninja / Upstart Golden / Gearfried / Fire Flint / Soma

Mitsu / Tobari / Getsuga  ->  Soma  ->  Mitsu / Tobari / Getsuga



Alright, that about does it! I hope you enjoyed this list and that it got you thinking about some possible extensions/additions you could make to the Ninja list! If you have any questions or comments, or have suggestions for this build, please let me know in the comments! I appreciate you, and hope you have a good day!

deck_excerpt: Pure Unadulterated Gishki Deck Post PHHY
deck_description:
Gishki recieved 4 new pieces of legacy support in PHHY and they are all really good. Gishki now have the ability to set up Turn 1 boards with interruptions rather than just existing as a gimmicky handloop Deck. This is a pure Gishki Deck that uses the new Gishki support. At the very least, your Turn 1 board will have 2-3 monster negates, I:P Masquerena, 2 to 4 cards in hand and proper follow-up.

For our monsters, we play 1 Gishki Zielgigas, 2 Evigishki Nereimanas, 1 Evigishki Gustkraken, 2 Gishki Abyss, 3 Gishki Shadow, 3 Gishki Vision, and 3 Grim Gishki. Zielgigas is a massive 3200 ATK body that allows you to pay 1000 LP to draw a card and spin a card on field if the card you drew was a Gishki monster. While you won't be Summoning him Turn 1, he is still good Ritual fodder for the new Level 10 Gishki Ritual and he can net you advantage on Turn 3 onwards. Nereimanas is the new Gishki Ritual from PHHY and it is extremely good. On Ritual Summon, it can revive any WATER monster from GY including another copy of itself and it is not once per turn. Also, it can negate a monster effect and shuffle it into the Deck by returning a Gishki Ritual Monster you control to hand as an effect rather than cost and it is a soft once per turn. Not only can this card allow you to put up multiple monster negates if you Summon multiples, it also gives synergy with another card called Aquamirror Illusion which can Summon back the Nereimanas you returned to hand for another monster negate. Gustkraken on Ritual Summon looks at 2 random cards in your opponent's hand and you shuffle one of them back into Deck. This card is more of an additional play that you can make going first since this card aims to make a board rather than handloop. If you want, you can replace it with a 3rd Nereimanas since the possibility of Summoning a 3rd is definitely there. Gishki Abyss searches any Gishki with 1000 or less DEF on Summon which is not once per turn. This basically searches everything in your Deck aside from Nereimanas, so if you can keep Summoning it over and over again, you can search a ton of cards. You will usually be using it to search Gishki Shadow and Gishki Vision. Both can be an entire Tribute for a WATER Ritual Monster and they can discard themselves to search a Gishki card which is not a once per turn. Shadow discards itself to search a Gishki Ritual Spell while Vision discards itself to search a Gishki Ritual Monster. Both of these cards are insane and with them not being once per turn, you are able to search out the necessary cards to Ritual Summon as long as you have copies of them in hand. Grim Gishki can also be used as an entire Tribute for a WATER Ritual Monster and it can Summon any Gishki monster from Deck on Summon. This basically gets you to Gishki Abyss making it a starter and somewhat of a 1 card combo starter.

For handtraps, we play 1 Nibiru, the Primal Being and 3 Ash Blossom. Ash is good in general, but it and Nibiru are in here as Crossout Designator targets since this Deck is very subseptible to handtraps and disruptions. 

For Spells/Traps: We have 1 Gishki Photomirror and 3 Gishki Aquamirror. Photomirror Ritual Summons by paying 500 LP for each Level on your Ritual Monster. While this means that you will be paying 5000 Life Points to Summon Nereimanas, not having to Tribute monsters is really good for conserving resources. Aquamirror is a normal Ritual Spell for the archetype and it can shuffle itself into Deck from GY to add back a Gishki Ritual Monster in GY which is good for recycling. We are not playing Gishki Icemirror as we are already using up 5000 Life Points for Photomirror, so Icemirror dealing DMG to you equal to the Ritual Monster's ATK is pretty bad considering it can either kill you or put you in a very precarious situation. However, it is still a good card for the archetype since its 2nd effect works well with Zielgigas. 3 Aquamirror Focalization. This searches any Gishki Monster and it can banish itself during the End Phase to set any Aquamirror Spell/Trap from Deck or GY. Not only does it provide more consitency, but it gives access to Aquamirror Illusion which synergizes very well with Nereimanas as I explained earlier. 1 Called by the Grave and 3 Crossout Designator. To reiterate, this Deck is very subseptible to handtraps and disruptions, so you need to protect yourself against those as best as you can. 3 Pot of Prosperity for more consistency. 3 Salvage which is like a godsend in this Deck. It basically adds back Shadow and Vision from GY which nets you more resources. And since it is not once per turn, you can amass a ton of resources if you have multiples in hand. 3 Infinite Impermanence for disruption, but it is also a Crossout Target. 1 Aquamirror Illusion. This card is good for reasons that I have already explained and Focalization can set it from GY so you only need to play 1. 

Extra Deck only requires a few necessary monsters for your combo, so the rest can realistically be filled with anything of your choice. I am playing 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder, 1 Downerd Magician, and 1 Sky Cavalry of Centaurea. This is just a small Zeus package. You can also play Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Gustav Max and Superdreadnought Rail Cannon Juggernaut Liebe since this Deck can make Rank 10's, but I would rather not use my Ritual Monsters for Xyz Materials. 1 Herald of Pure Light and 1 Gigantic Spright. These are very playable Rank 2's in this Deck with Pure Light being able to add back a monster from GY and Gigantic Spright being able to do something like Summon a Gishki Abyss from Deck at the end of your combo to search follow-up. 2 Elder Entity N'tss and 1 EvilTwin's Trouble Sunny as Ultimate Slayer Targets. 1 Accesscode Talker and 1 Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax. Avramax could realistically be any Link-4 you want to you into with I:P. 1 Knightmare Unicorn and 1 I:P Masquerena. And finally, 1 Marincess Coral Anemone and 2 Spright Elf. Elf can be made with Abyss and Grim and then it can Summon back the Abyss for another search. After your first Nereimanas Summon, you will have 2 extra WATER monsters on field which can be used to go into Anemone to Summon back Abyss again for another search. 

Side Deck consists of 1 Nibiru, 3 Ghost Ogre, 1 Effect Veiler, 1 EvilTwins Ki-sikil & Lil-la, 2 Cosmic Cyclone and 1 Harpie's Feather Duster, 3 Ultimate Slayer, and 3 Dark Ruler No More. If you think that Cosmic is a bit much considering that you've already paid 5000 LP with Photomirror, Twin Twisters also works. Also, Veiler is only here as another Crossout target, but it can be changed for any relevant handtrap in the current meta that severely hurts this such as something like Droll & Lock Bird.

deck_excerpt: Degeneracy has never been so hot!
deck_description:
Introduction:

 

A deck inspired/stolen/sourced/learned from MBT's "Mine at Home" video -- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2LeFR-1sIk8 -- which has been making the rounds across MD and since there didn't appear to be a deck here on YGO Pro I'd figured I'd be the first.

 

The goal of the deck, as the video shows, is rather simple:

1. Set Fire Prison -- which you may search with Pots, Demise of the Land, or Terraforming -- so only Link Monsters can attack.

2. Lock down your opponent's board with Floodgates and Ojamas.

3. Win via Cauldron of the Old Man or by deck out.

 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 

Adjustments from the Video:

 

While the video's version is stellar, I've made a few modifications.

 

1) Lava Golem + Gadarla, the Mystery Dust Kaiju: Including a kaiju of choice and a pair of golems. This helps to break boards going second, and if you can set a golem on their field along with Fire Prison with a Floodgate of choice -- and perhaps some added S/T negation from Dark Bribe or Solemn -- you can not only lock your opponent out of the game but set them on a path of accelerated burning. I have found having four of these breakers works best after testing in Ranked. However, it may be best to change the kaiju given its wind type and Floo's popularity. Open to adjustment.

 

2) DNA Surgery: A card that isn't very necessary but can sometimes be a fun tech. Surgery can allow you to change your Ojamas to Fiends and toss some Golems on your opponent's side of the field. You can also use Surgery to change link Monsters to Cyberse type and have Fire Prison's second effect take over for getting as close to Mystic Mine as you can. This card is certainly the weakest part of this deck, but I don't believe this deck is at its most optimal, much less competitive anyways.

 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 

Pros and Cons:

 

Pros: 

1. Extreme power to lock the opponent down when going first.

2. Little skill needed to learn (certified Yes Clicker stamp of approval).

3. Be a YGO War Criminal.

4. Fairly UR cheap with unneeded Extra Deck.

5. Works wonders in a format where most players run one piece of S/T removal via Duster, 

 

Cons: 

1. Extreme disadvantage going second, relies on drawing the out via board breaker.

2. Little skill needed to learn (certified former Numeron player stamp of approval).

3. Be a YGO War Criminal.

4. Exceptionally weak against some control decks. Sky Striker and Eldlich eat this deck for breakfast.

5. Suspectable to Ash given you will likely not draw all your needed cards and could brick with too many pots.

6. Friend destroyer.

7. A continued contribution to the horrid Master Duel format.

8. Takes an extreme amount of time compared to most duels in a way that is not interactive.

9. Ojamas.

10. It will likely be used frequently in the upcoming Synchro x Xyz Festival and you will not have fun. I will not have fun. No one will have fun. Be the better person.

 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 

Potential Additions:

 

Most of the cards in this deck are needed -- sorry in advance for the high amount of SR -- but there are certain modifications that wouldn't hurt. Here are a few potential additions, albeit most being UR.

 

1. Metaverse for an extra searcher for Fire Prison.

2. Final Countdown for an alternative win condition and added pressure.

3. Exodia the Forbidden One for a riskier, if more dramatic, alternative win condition.

4. One Day of Peace or Upstart Goblin for more draw power.

5. Pot of Desires for even more draw power, albeit at risk of losing your key cards.

 

Other suggestions could be replacing kaijus, adding board breakers, or really anything which could assist with going second. With the recent Branded support, additional protection against a Guardian Chimera play -- which is likely to destroy two of your cards on your turn -- could also be advised. Either way, this deck offers mutability.

 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 

Conclusion:

 

If you're looking for a low-skill, low UR budget, coin toss dependent, degenerate, floodgate-ridden deck which wins via burning, stalling, and boring your opponent to defeat, this may be the deck for you. The world is your oyster, and unfortunately, this deck is as well.

 

Have fun!
Approximately $30 Generaiders

The goal of this deck is midrange, going first and/or second.

1. If you go first, try to dump Slifer into the GY by using True Name and/or Branded Fusion and then search to use Revived Sky God to your advantage, right after you set up the DM-Circle-Nav/Eternal combo, so you can have a floodgate and banish on your opponents turn while drawing 6 cards (as your opponent draws 0 if they have 6 from their normal draw). 

2. If you go second, most likely your opponent will have a negate board with mainly 2 or more monsters, so the goal is to tribute at least 3 of them (your choice) by summoning Sphere Mode. Then using DM with DM Attack to clear the backrow, using the DM-Circle-Nav/Eternal combo for next turn, OR using Branded to summon DMtDK for the boardlock with Eternal and/or using Branded to summon Dragoon.

*Meklord Exist*

Everything else:......

Of course mystic mine because the sheer power is insane and the runick cards allow easy access to the mystic mine cards for board breaking or just mill with Runick Allure. The Tri-Brigade engine is a powerful engine that also goes well with the Beast Runick Monster. I added the Knightmare mosters and Masq for easy aces to the link zones when the Runick Monster takes up the EMZ. Overall this is a real contender for one of the best Runick Decks. Tri-Brigade is back. LETS GO!

Hello guys and I'm back again on sharing decks and searching opinions and ideas, with my real life D/D/D build. Enjoy!
deck_description:
This is a budget D/D/D list that I own in real life and use in my locals. The build itself is pretty stale and that kinda makes me sad so as always I ask for your opinions in the comments. 

Since I don't plan on explaining my main deck choices I will make up by explaining my side deck choices.

Kaijus: As you can understand I side in Kaijus in case I have to second against a deck that brings out troublesome monsters that I would not like to deal with (some kind of negate - Toad for instance). Specifically, Gadarla is a pretty mainstream way to deal with Floos (although I only own 1 copy of her)

Harpie's Feather Duster / Twin Twisters: Well classic backrow removal cards since I happen to face trap based decks (Floodlich for instance) pretty often

Dark Hole: By no means I suggest using this card. The real reason I run this one in my side is 'cause (along with DRNM) it's a pretty famous meme in our local community. Still it can do it's job.

Forbidden Chalice: This is my ultra budget alternative to Infinite Impermance since I still haven't bought my playset. Although a versatile card I firmly believe that Impermance is much better in the current meta so I would prefer running it instead. Nevertheless, Forbidden Chalice provides a potential negate.

Contract with Eternal Darkness: Is there really anything to say about this card? It's effect is pretty insane and can help in a variety of matchups (although it won't help much against decks like Tears and Sprights and that's my reason for running Patent License on main instead).

Contract with the Errors: This is an immense countermeasure for trap decks and it's ofc my trump card against them

Contract with the WItch: A classic way to fight against cards like DRNM and Droplet, since it allows Siegfried to negate them by becoming the CL3 (CL1 - DRNM, CL2 - Witch, CL3 - Siegfried)

Dimensional Barrier: One of the strongest floodgates in the format nothing more to say

Necrovalley Jumpscare! The infamous field spell is what made Gravekeeper's popular but wait, there's more. Activate Necrovalley ----> Summon Spiritualist ---> Summon Supernaturalist ----> Activate Hidden Temples ----> Activate Royal Tribute ----> Win the Game. It's the dream combo which many Gravekeeper Decks focus on but what do you do if that doesn't work? Well this Deck uses all the other better Gravekeeper Cards to have a weaker Plan B which does work quite often (Surprisingly). Let's go a bit more into Detail: 

 

The many different options

Gravekeeper's are slow but often they can get enough time through their various lockdown cards to get things started. With Burn, Crush and Beatdown options they can achieve the victory in various slower ways. They can prevent Special summoning and any interaction that is Graveyard related. They can even prevent the activation of other Field Spell cards too.

Cannonholder burns for 700 without a Once Per turn making it a stronger Cannon Soldier for Gravekeeper's only. Descendant destroys Cards without a Once Per Turn again. Both require Tributes instead which can be created through various ways within this Deck. You got recycling and Revival Power in the S & T lineup. You also got a few slower ways to Special Monsters directly from Deck which is nice too.

The Big Boys in the Maindeck Oracle and Visionary can both be summoned with just one Tribute. Visionary is easily the strongest attacker and Oracle has some nice removal and weakening options build within. Him being Level 10 makes him the best Fusion Material for Supernaturalist on top of that. 

A Omni Negation Counter Trap with Condition and no Cost and Supernaturalist as a very strong Fusion Boss are strong options on top of that. Your Main Card Necrovalley can be searched and recovered in many ways and should always be active. Both Supernaturalist and Shaman protect your field Spell from harm. The Priestess can act as Necrovalley too which is a good alternative if you can't find Necrovalley. 

 

The Problems

Did you know Gravekeeper's were the first real Archetype ever? So you can kinda imagine there's some trouble ahead. One of your key Cards being Royal Tribute is unsearchable same goes for a Rite of Spirit and Gravekeeper's Stele. 

Some Gravekeeper's revolve around Flip Summoning which is way to slow to always work nowadays. You often find yourself in a Situation were you play your Flip Monster Face Up to get a Hidden Temples of Necrovalley active. 

And maybe the biggest downside is the absolute necessity of having Necrovalley active at any time to even work properly. 

Overall the Tempo of this Deck is slow and if you don't get to go first there's often trouble ahead. Be mindful of that when you consider trying this Strategy. Then again if you go first you will win against the most Meta relevant Strategies with ease.

 

Final Words

All in all this Deck works just well and consistent most of the time. I used it to grind my way to Diamond in Master Duel once but since then found other types of Decks more easy to get there. It's quite good and you might wanna give it a try! 

Overall Rating:

deck_excerpt: Blue-Eyes, With Eyes of Blue, Casual
deck_description:
Hey it's Brick Eyes hooray.... but wait this one doesn't even brick that much and focuses on the well rounded With Eyes of Blue Strategy. Let's go into more Detail:

 

With Eyes of Blue

The Goal of this Deck is to use the "With Eyes of Blue" cards to it's maximum to gain advantage. Unlike other Blue-Eyes Decks this one doesn't brick often and can summon BE Spirit Dragon and BE Twin Burst Dragon as early as turn 1. Use the powerful trap Ultimate Creature of Destruction and both recovery and search to repeat your go to Combo plus Ultimate Fusion for the big unexpected hit or Dragon Beacon of white to get a Blue-Eyes Monster which can easily attack 10+ times and finish the game. 

The Priestess can Recycle Blue-Eyes back into the Deck which makes the desperation Move "Rage with Eyes of Blue" live whenever you draw it. Having a searchable Raigeki thanks to the Field Spells Graveyard effect being able to search Burst Stream of Destruction is the Cherry on top for this otherwise streamlined Archetype.

Yes there's more too this which I can't explain in full detail here but overall Blue-Eyes is a Simple to understand Strategy. The most unique part to this day with Blue-Eyes White Dragon is, that he's the unbeaten Champion in terms of ATK for Normal Monsters. Blue-Eyes Ultimate Dragon is the King of ATK for non-effect Monsters too. 

 

The obvious Problems

As good as all of it sounds your plays are quite limited and the Deck is missing some bigger surprises but in the right hands it's certainly better then your average Chaos MAX Dragon beatdown deck and looking at Master Duel you get swiftly to Platin League with it (Diamond is kinda a stretch with it). 

You will sometimes find yourself in Situations with no Out against certain Cards the opponent is using. A Blue-Eyes Deck wants to overwhelm the opponent with strong beaters and strong defense but that's about it. Finest Kaiba Style Gameplay.

 

Final Words

Lastly this Deck for reallife play is very Budget friendly compared to other Blue-Eyes variants and stays true to it's Blue-Eyes cards only. Give it a try if you like pure Archetype Decks or if you like to play a more simple type of Deck. I do find myself having fun to simply beatdown the opponent with pure Strength sometimes. 

Overall Rating:

deck_description: This deck is kinda gas, lol

Your favorite cartoons are back! 

Now with some help from their Performapals, these toons are ready to entertain you once again with an exciting new show just for you!

 

Deck strategies:

Use "Performapal Gongato" as protection against direct attacks

(this helps to stall until you get your toon engine going)

Use "Performapal Guitartle" for an extra draw whilst setting up your pendulum scales

Pendulum summon "Red-Eyes Toon Dragon"/"Toon Dark Magician" and use it's effect to summon the level 8 toons

("Toon Ancient Gear Golem" and "Toon Black Luster Soldier" can't be summoned with your pendulum scales because at max they can only summon level 7s)

Use "Perfomapal Drummerilla" to give your toons a little extra damage

(Useful if you need that little bit of extra damge to OTK or to protect your toon monsters in the case that you don't havce toon kindom on your board yet)

Use "Pendulum Switch" to summon out your pendulum monster and then return them to your scale in combination with "Performapal Guitartle" to continuiously get extra draws

(Best use for this is to summon out the pendulum at the end of your turn and then return it to your spell/trap zone during the start of your opponent's turn)

 

I hope you find this deck as fun as I do.

Cheers,

I just won locals for the first time (4:0 against IDS, Swordsoul, Adventurer dragon link and Rikka Sunavalon) with this deck and decided to post it because I can barely find any lists of this hybrid. Mathmech Circular is a great card that can almost get you to the basic end board (I:P Masquerena and Decode Talker Heatsoul with an active Mathmech Superfactorial) on it's own by sending Mathmech Sigma, then summon it to search for Superfactorial with Circular and to go into Primathmech Alembertian, who then searches for Mathmech Diameter, which gets you to 4 of the 5 bodies you need if you go into Splash Mage. Superfactorial really helps with one of Salamangreats biggest problems, Nibiru the primal being, because you will still have at least 2 disruptions as long as it resolves even if your whole field gets tributed. The fact that Circular provides you with 2 Cyberse on the field without using your normal summon also helps a lot going second because Salamangreat sometimes struggled if the normal summon or link 1 got removed.

The Salamangreat cards can give you additional extenders to get to the basic endboard (or even end on an additional link 1, which means that you can use that link 1 with I:P Masquerena and the Primathmech Laplacian that you summon with Superfactorial to go into Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax on your oppononents turn instead of using Heatsoul for that) and they also add grindgame capability because cards like Salamangreat Spinny and Salamangreat Jack Jaguar allow you to go into link climbs as long as you have a Cyberse monster and a Salamangreat Balelynx in the extra deck. This enables easy Accesscode Talker lines through Splash Mage, Transcode Talker and Update Jammer (the double attack from Jammer is especially important after you use Circulars first effect because you can only attack with 1 monster that turn, so you need double attack Accesscode to OTK).
